This is my second 30 day yoga practice in a row (finished dedicate, loved it) and this was the most challenging practice yet. First, I forced myself to do it, even though (perhaps laziness, perhaps not) I didnt want to, so I had a begrudging outlook from the start -- and Adriene called them out at the very beginning -- checking a box, which is exactly what I wanted to be able to do by the end of this practice, fear of not progressing on my timeline, which isn't the best motivation for doing yoga, and even more so in my case, as a spiritual practice. I was chugging along, breathing and centering myself, until that was all I could do, barely able to keep myself positively in the moment. And then my thoughts hijacked the practice, the seeds i planted before the practice started began to grow and count down the minutes on the matt that i typically cherish and want more of.. I had all kinds of nasty thoughts ("uggh, I wish she had chosen something differen, I wish that was the last pose, i wish she would slow downt" -- this practice, for me, was deceptively hard)  in my head by the final downward dog of the final flow, but once we landed at the end in cross legged seat, after we brought our hands to our heart -- I felt aware of my previous harsh thoughts, yet not consumed by them, almost seperate. It was a good feeling, to be able to accept and not judge i felt a certain unsavory way in the moment, yet by the end, grateful id pushed through and experienced it at all. Im excited to come back tomorrow -- this time with a better attitude!! I plant the seeds for a great practice tomorrow in this moment today. Namaste to you, Adriene, and to all other yogis as we all learn to walk this beautiful, challenging, and enriching path. We say that getting on the mat is the hardest part -- and it truly is. Its easy to take our time and energy for granted. We go through the motions, we become complacent, and we miss opportunities of gratitude and often belatedly recognize the gratitude we couldve had in the moment. While I always feel its better to reflect and appreciate after the fact, I can't help but wonder, how would the experience change for me if I paired it with gratitude in the moment? A spiritual experiment awaits!

Dear Adriene, Day 12 opened my eyes so much! LAST night I came to the mat in the early evening after taking the dog for walk and so I was ready and wide awake for today's session.

Once again, I struggled with some of the stretches, especially the one where you from plank to left and right twists to the floor.  I would love to know an alternative to this practice because it also popped up in today's (Day 13) and my feet kept on slipping out from under me and I was having an awkward time on the mat, but once again, I really came out of the whole experience feeling so much better.  There is definitely something with this yoga that is making me feel really good at the end and I can understand why so many people take this journey and stay on it.  

I am also challenging myself and by doing this it gives me something to achieve along the way, especially when poses and positions crop up again and again. It is also good to know that Adriene also has a routine with the days, and so you get use to what is to come next.  While following along Adriene said something about taking your time moving with the flow and I said to myself "it's not the destination, its the journey" when she said about not rushing to get to the pose/position ... so from now, I am seeing where I am on going and I am being surprised as what is at the end destination when we arrive.  The destination is a bit over 15 days and what will I experience on this journey will depend on what I want to put into it, and how I will treat myself and what I will learn along the way.  

I am looking forward to staying on this path as the journey so far has been so good that I do feel calmer and refreshed after each day on the mat.
